Overview

Jonathan and Katie have small RNA data for 6 almond samples (3 from each of two age groups). Data are SE50, sequenced by Novogene, and are at /fs/project/PAS0471/osu9453/AgeCohortProject/SmallRNASeq/RawData

Analysis Workflow

workflow

Adaptor Trimming: Trimmomatic W/Score 6

Trim adaptors and low quality bases with Trimmomatic - dropped the threshold score to 6 because of the nature of these short reads.

#script 6_trimmomatic_batch_2.sh

mkdir trim_job_scripts
mkdir trimmed_fastq2

for i in `ls /fs/project/PAS0471/osu9453/AgeCohortProject/SmallRNASeq/RawData`

do

samp=`echo ${i} | sed -E 's/(.fq.gz)//'`
 {
 echo '#PBS -l walltime=02:00:00'
 echo '#PBS -l nodes=1:ppn=3'
 echo '#PBS -A PAS1755'
 echo '#PBS -j oe'

 echo 'cd $PBS_O_WORKDIR'
 echo 'module load trimmomatic'
 echo 'java -jar $TRIMMOMATIC SE -phred33 /fs/project/PAS0471/osu9453/AgeCohortProject/SmallRNASeq/RawData/'${i} 'trimmed_fastq2/'${samp}'.fq.gz ILLUMINACLIP:adaptors/adaptors.fa:2:30:6 LEADING:3 TRAILING:3 SLIDINGWINDOW:6:20 MINLEN:12'

 } > trim_job_scripts/job_trim${base}_2.sh

 qsub trim_job_scripts/job_trim${base}_2.sh

done

Get Read Size Distribution Data

Checking the distribution of read sizes after trimming adaptors. Expect a lot of reads in the ~18-25 bp range.

#script 7_read_sizes.sh

mkdir read_sizes_6

for i in `ls trimmed_fastq2/*.fq.gz`

do

samp=`echo ${i} | sed -E 's/(.+)(..._.+_.+)(.fq.gz)/\2/'`
 {
 echo '#PBS -l walltime=01:00:00'
 echo '#PBS -l nodes=1:ppn=1'
 echo '#PBS -A PAS1755'
 echo '#PBS -j oe'

 echo 'cd $PBS_O_WORKDIR'
 echo "zcat "${i}" | grep -E '^[ATGCN]{5,}' | awk '{print length}' | sort | uniq -c | sed -E 's/^[[:blank:]]+//' | sed -E 's/[[:space:]]/,/' | awk 'BEGIN{OFS=\",\"} {print \$0,\"$samp\"}' > read_sizes_6/"${samp}".txt"
 } > read_size_jobs/${samp}_6.sh

 qsub read_size_jobs/${samp}_6.sh

done

#script 8_cat_read_sizes.sh
cat read_sizes_6/* > all_sizes_6.txt

Summary

This Shortstack run was with default parameters. Shortstack provides a number of result files. Results.txt, Unplaced.txt, and Counts.txt seem to be the primary ones. It appears the Results.txt file contains results for sequences that could be confidently assigned to a single location in the genome (uniquely mapped). These are placed into bins and each bin is annotated in the Results file with a consensus sequence. Shortstack also keeps track of other small RNAs. These are reported in a separate file “Unplaced.txt”, and each individual sequence is reported separately. The “Counts.txt” file has read counts for each sample for each sequence, and includes unplaced seqs.

Blast Aligned Seqs To miRBase (7 Species)

Here we’re getting the sequences associated with the two aligned files (Results.txt and Unplaced.txt) and blasting them to a filtered version of the “mature.fa” database from mirBase, which was filtered to include Prunus, Arabidopsis, Malus, Glycine, Medicago, Populus, and Solanum. Used the parameters “-evalue 1 -task blastn-short -word_size 4 -gapopen 25 -gapextend 10 -reward 5 -penalty -4 -dust no -soft_masking false”, which I think are equivalent to doing a Blast search through the miR website, with the exception that the evalue is set to 1 here instead of 10 online. I think 1 is still pretty liberal, so we’ll apply additional filters below.

Get Seqs To Blast

#script 6_get_results_to_blast.sh
grep -v '#' ShortStack_1644852191/Results.txt | cut -f1,9 > temp_res.txt

#script 7_Results_to_blast.pl (puts seqs from Results.txt into fasta format)

#! /usr/bin/perl
use warnings;
use strict;

open IN, "temp_res.txt" or die$!;
open OUT, ">Results_to_blast.fa";

my $name;
my $seq;

while(<IN>) {
        
      my @temp = split (/\t/, "$_");
      print OUT ">$temp[0]\n";
      print OUT "$temp[1]";
        
}

#script 8_Unplaced_to_blast.pl (puts seqs from Unplaced.txt into fasta format)

#! /usr/bin/perl
use warnings;
use strict;

open IN, "ShortStack_1644852191/Unplaced.txt" or die$!;
open OUT, ">Unplaced_to_blast.fa";

while(<IN>) {
        
        if ($_ =~ /^\#/) {
                next;
        }
        
        else {
                my @temp = split (/\t/, "$_");
                my $seq = $temp[0];
                print OUT ">$seq\n";
                print OUT "$seq\n";     
        }
        
} 

#script 9_cat_blast_input.sh
cat Results_to_blast.fa Unplaced_to_blast.fa > all_blast_input.fa

Create Blast Database

Downloaded “mature.fa” file, from mirBase, filtered for the 7 target species, and used it to create a blast database.

#script 10_get_mirBase.sh (download the mature miRs database from mirBase)
curl -L -o mirBase_mature.fa.gz https://www.mirbase.org/ftp/CURRENT/mature.fa.gz
gunzip mirBase_mature.fa.gz


#script 11_extract_targets.pl (filter the database file for the 7 target species)
#! /usr/bin/perl
use warnings;
use strict;

my $TargetSeq = "no";
my $print = "no";

open IN, "mirBase_mature.fa" or die$!;
open OUT, ">Targets_miRBase.fa";

while(<IN>) {
        
        if ($_ =~ /(>.+Prunus.+)|(>.+Arabidopsis.+)|(>.+Malus.+)|(>.+Glycine.+)|(>.+Medicago.+)|(>.+Populus.+)|(>.+Solanum.+)/) {
                $print = "yes";
                print OUT "$_";
        }
        
        elsif ($_ =~ />/) {
                $print = "no";
        }       
        
        else {
                if ($print eq "yes") {
                        print OUT "$_";
                }       
        }
        
} 

#script 12_make_blast_db.sh

mkdir blast_db
module load blast
makeblastdb -dbtype nucl -in Targets_miRBase.fa -out blast_db/Targets_miRBase

Run Blast (blastn-short)

Ran blastn (Blast version 2.10.0+) with parameters equivalent to an online Blast through mirBase website.

#script 19_blast_short_all_w_seqs_slen.job

#PBS -l walltime=03:00:00
#PBS -l nodes=1:ppn=2
#PBS -A PAS1755
#PBS -j oe

cd $PBS_O_WORKDIR

module load blast
blastn -evalue 1 -task blastn-short -word_size 4 -gapopen 25 -gapextend 10 -reward 5 -penalty -4 -dust no -soft_masking false -db blast_db/Targets_miRBase -query all_blast_input.fa -out blast_out_all_seqs_eval1.txt -outfmt "6 qseqid sseqid qstart qend sstart send evalue length pident qseq sseq slen length"

Extract Best Hit For Each Query

A given query sequence could have multiple valid Blast hits (valid hits to multiple species, etc). If multiple hits share the best evalue for a given query (a tie), each hit will be listed in the “hits” column. Then filter to just retain the best evalue for each query sequence.

#summarize on query and evalue and create column with all subjects with that eval
#then arrange and distinct on query and evalue to retain the best one.

blast_sum <- blast_res %>%
   group_by(query, evalue) %>%
   summarize("hits" = paste(subject, collapse = "; "),
             "length" = paste(length, collapse = "; "),
             "pct_iden" = paste(pct_identity, collapse = "; "),
             "query_seq" = paste(qseq, collapse = "; "),
             "db_seq" = paste(sseq, collapse = "; "),
             "db_len" = paste(slen, collapse = "; "),
             "align_len" = paste(align_len, collapse = "; "))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'query'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
#distinct to just retain the best evalue for each query
blast_sum_filt <- blast_sum %>%
  arrange(query, evalue) %>%
  distinct(query, .keep_all = TRUE)

Differential Expression (DESeq) Analysis

Preview Counts Table From Shortstack

Using the Counts.txt file from Shortstack as input, which includes read counts for each sample for each small RNA identified, including unplaced sequences (multiple mappers).

Prep Data

library(DESeq2)
library(RColorBrewer)

counts <- read_tsv(file = "Counts.txt", col_names = TRUE, col_types = "cciiiiiii") 
samples<-read_tsv(file="samples.txt", col_names = TRUE, show_col_types = FALSE)

counts_matrix <- counts %>% 
  dplyr::select(4:9) %>% as.matrix()

se <- SummarizedExperiment(assays = counts_matrix, colData = samples)
se@elementMetadata@rownames <- counts$Locus
dds <- DESeqDataSet(se, design = ~age)

Perform DE Analysis For 6yr vs 1yr Expression Levels

fitAge<-DESeq(dds)
DEG_res <- results(fitAge, alpha = 0.1, contrast=c("age", "6yr", "1yr"))
DEG_res <- data.frame(DEG_res, row.names = rownames(DEG_res))
DEG_res <- DEG_res %>% mutate("ID" = se@elementMetadata@rownames)

#Join the Blast hits in to the DE results by sequence ID
blast_sum_filt <- blast_sum_filt  %>%
  rename("query" = "ID",
         "hits" = "blast_hits")
DEG_res <- left_join(x = DEG_res, y = blast_sum_filt, by = "ID")

Add Columns To DE Results

  • seq: The sequences originally coming from the Unplaced.txt file are identified by their sequence, but those coming from the Results.txt file (uniquely aligned) are identified by their genome coordinates, so adding in a column that stores the sequence for each.
results_seqs <- read_tsv("Results.txt") %>% dplyr::select(1,9)
names(results_seqs) <- c("ID", "seq")
DEG_res <- left_join(x = DEG_res, y = results_seqs, by = "ID")
DEG_res$seq[is.na(DEG_res$seq)] <- DEG_res$ID[is.na(DEG_res$seq)]

Mark Significant miRs and Get -log10p For Volcano Plot

  • ‘-log10p’: negative log10(padj) to be used for volcano plot
  • sig: Identifies significant small RNAs, defined as padj < 0.01 and an absolute Log2FoldChange > 2.
  • miR_family: for small RNAs with a Blast hit, the name of the miR they Blasted to is edited to reflect the miR family. For example, miR156a and miR156b would both be assigned to miR156.
DEG_res <- DEG_res %>% 
  mutate("-log10p" = -log10(padj),
         "sig" = ifelse((padj < 0.01 & (abs(log2FoldChange) > 2)), "Y", "N"),
         "miR_family" = stringr::str_remove(blast_hits, ";.+"))

DEG_res$miR_family <- stringr::str_remove(DEG_res$miR_family, "...-")
DEG_res$miR_family <- stringr::str_remove(DEG_res$miR_family, "-[35]p")
DEG_res$miR_family <- stringr::str_remove(DEG_res$miR_family, "[a-z]$")
DEG_res$miR_family <- stringr::str_remove(DEG_res$miR_family, "^\\s")

Write Results Table To File

This file has DE analysis results (including padj and log2fold change) for all analyzed small RNAs. Rows with an entry in the “ID” column that has genome coordinates represent sequences that aligned uniquely (grouped into bins by Shortstack with consensus sequence). If the “ID” column has a sequence, it’s a small RNA that Shortstack identified, but was unplaced. Each unique unplaced sequence is reported separately. Positive log2 fold changes indicate upregulation in 6yr samples with respect to 1yr samples.

For the small RNAs associated with a Blast hit(s) that passed the filtering, those blast hits are included, along with the identity of the sequence that was Blasted (column “seq”; sequence from Shortstack), the aligned portion of the sequence that was Blasted (column “query seq”), and the aligned portion of the sequence from miRbase (mature miR) the sequence Blasted to (column “db_seq”).

write.table(DEG_res, file = "all_DE_results_w_aligned_seqs.csv", sep = ",", quote = FALSE, col.names = TRUE, row.names = FALSE)

Volcano Plot - Assigned miRs

This volcano plot has data for only the set of small RNAs that were assigned confidently to a mature miR from miRbase (Blast evalue < 0.1 & aligned length >= (mature miR length - 2)). There are 455 of these (out of the 60578 total small RNAs identified by Shortstack). Those with a padj value <=0.01 are colored based on their miR family (i.e. miR156a & miR156b would be grouped into miR156). These colored points cover a lot of the miR families identified in the “DE miR family” analysis below that are robust to evalue thresholds.

#split the data into two data frames - one with points that will be colored, and one with all other points.

to_color <- DEG_res %>%
  dplyr::filter(!is.na(padj)) %>%
  dplyr::filter(evalue <= 0.1) %>% 
  dplyr::filter(padj <= 0.01) %>%
  dplyr::select(log2FoldChange, `-log10p`, padj, sig, miR_family)

not_colored <- DEG_res %>% 
  dplyr::filter(!is.na(padj)) %>%
  dplyr::filter(evalue < 0.1) %>% 
  #dplyr::filter(padj > 0.01) %>%
  dplyr::select(log2FoldChange, `-log10p`, padj, sig, miR_family)

ggplot(not_colored %>% filter(!is.na(sig)), aes(x = log2FoldChange, y = `-log10p`, shape = sig))  +
  geom_point(size = 2, color = "gray") + 
  theme_classic() +
  labs(y = "-log10(padj", x = "Log2FoldChange", 
       title = "Expression Patterns For Small RNAs Assigned To miRs: 1-yr Vs 6-yr Almonds",
       subtitle = "Positive Fold Changes Indicate Upregulation in 6-yr Samples Vs 1-yr Samples")  +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
  geom_point(data = to_color, aes(x = log2FoldChange, y = `-log10p`, color = miR_family), inherit.aes = FALSE, shape = 17, size = 2)

Overlap Analysis

Katie sent the coordinates for the 17 DMRs they identified. This analysis compares each of those to the set of coordinates associated with uniquely mapped differentially expressed small RNAs identified from the Shortstack/DEseq analysis to see if there is any overlap.

In each analysis below, if the sum is 1, then the query region (Katie’s DMR) overlaps with at least one of the DE miR regions by at least one bp. A sum of zero indicates no overlap. The “buffer” argument pads the target coordinates (in this case, the DE miRs) by the given value on each side.

contains_func <- function(target, query, buffer = 0) {
  target_chr <- stringr::str_remove(target, ":.+")
  query_chr <- stringr::str_remove(query, ":.+")
  
  target_min <- stringr::str_replace(target, "(.+:)(.+)(-.+)", "\\2") %>% as.integer()
  target_max <- stringr::str_replace(target, "(.+:)(.+-)(.+)", "\\3") %>% as.integer()
  target_min <- target_min - buffer
  target_max <- target_max + buffer
  target_range <- target_min:target_max
  
  query_min <- stringr::str_replace(query, "(.+:)(.+)(-.+)", "\\2") %>% as.integer()
  query_max <- stringr::str_replace(query, "(.+:)(.+-)(.+)", "\\3") %>% as.integer()
  query_range <- query_min:query_max
  
  query_in_target <- ifelse(sum(query_range %in% target_range) > 0, "Y", "N")
  chr_match <- ifelse(target_chr == query_chr, "Y", "N")
  
  match <- ifelse(query_in_target == "Y" & chr_match == "Y", 1, 0)
  match
}

uniq_deg_fams <- function(blast_results, max_eval, maxp, min_l2fc) {
  
blast_res <- read_tsv(blast_results, col_names = FALSE)
names(blast_res) <- c("query", "subject", "qstart", "qend", "sstart", "send", "evalue", "length", "pct_identity", "qseq", "sseq", "slen")
blast_res <- blast_res %>% 
  mutate("align_len" = stringr::str_length(sseq))

blast_res <- blast_res %>% 
  dplyr::filter(align_len >= slen-2) %>%
  dplyr::filter(evalue <= max_eval)

blast_sum <- blast_res %>%
   group_by(query, evalue) %>%
   summarize("hits" = paste(subject, collapse = "; "),
             "length" = paste(length, collapse = "; "),
             "pct_iden" = paste(pct_identity, collapse = "; "),
             "query_seq" = paste(qseq, collapse = "; "),
             "db_seq" = paste(sseq, collapse = "; "),
             "db_len" = paste(slen, collapse = "; "),
             "align_len" = paste(align_len, collapse = "; "))

#distinct to just retain the best evalue for each query
blast_sum_filt <- blast_sum %>%
  arrange(query, evalue) %>%
  distinct(query, .keep_all = TRUE)

#Join the Blast hits in to the DE results by sequence ID
blast_sum_filt <- blast_sum_filt  %>%
  rename("query" = "ID",
         "hits" = "blast_hits")
DEG_res3 <- left_join(x = DEG_res2, y = blast_sum_filt, by = "ID")

results_seqs <- read_tsv("Results.txt") %>% dplyr::select(1,9)
names(results_seqs) <- c("ID", "seq")
DEG_res3 <- left_join(x = DEG_res3, y = results_seqs, by = "ID")
DEG_res3$seq[is.na(DEG_res3$seq)] <- DEG_res3$ID[is.na(DEG_res3$seq)]

sig_miRs <- DEG_res3 %>% 
  filter(padj < maxp & abs(log2FoldChange) > min_l2fc) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(blast_hits)) %>% pull(blast_hits) %>%
  stringr::str_split(";") %>% unlist() %>% stringr::str_remove("...-") %>%
  stringr::str_remove("-[35]p") %>%
  stringr::str_remove("[a-z]$") %>%
  stringr::str_remove("^\\s") %>%
  unique()

sig_miRs 
}
